# Building a shared mental model using manipulatives

#### In Module 3, you learned about Explore, Investigate, Practice, and Make (EIPM) sequences and how they are used in programming units to set students up for success. Now, let's zoom in on the role of the **Explore** lessons as foundational experiences that build a shared mental model for students.

## What is a shared mental model?

<div style="background-color: #a6e3e8; border-radius: 40px 40px 40px 40px; color: #000000; width: 95%; padding: 0.5px 20px 10px 20px;">

<p style="line-height: 1.5; margin-left: 10px; margin-right: 10px; margin-top: 20px; margin-bottom: 20px; font-size: 18px; ">

#### In the Code.org curriculum, a **shared mental model** is a mental model of a programming concept that is held in common by your students. We build these shared mental models through collaborative lesson activities that allow students to touch, move, and demonstrate relationships between objects that represent programming concepts. 
 </p>
 
</div>

##

#### For example, students can use materials as simple as plastic bags and sticky notes to demonstrate how variables can store information. Rather than diving in to assigning values to variables in a coding environment, students can see how information written on sticky notes can be "held" by a plastic baggie. This creates a foundation for their understanding of variables.
<br>

